<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-02-05T06:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-02-05T06:00:00-05:00" n="709" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d709">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 652.119/507</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Spain</hi> (<persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_WJE1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Willard</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Madrid</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-02-05T11:00:00+00:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">February 5, 1918, 11 a.m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received February 6, 1.53
                                    a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>1047. Supplementing Embassy’s 1042, February 4, 3 p.m., and referring
                                directly to Department’s 862, February 2, noon. It should be borne
                                in mind that Spain does not stand in the same relation to Central
                                Powers as do northern neutral powers, and that you can not deal with
                                Spain unless her racial pride is considered. She will never submit
                                to rationing as suggested nor does Embassy feel that she will agree
                                to charter her shipping above national necessities. If the
                                Department decides to postpone permanent agreement until Spain feels
                                more definitely necessity of coming to agreement with us, such
                                policy will be valueless so long as Spanish Ambassador at Washington
                                is able to secure permits to export all commodities needed in Spain,
                                notwithstanding our embargo, as is currently reported here.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_WJE1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Willard</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>